    <main>
        <h1>LeetCode 3666: Minimum Sum of Values by Dividing Array (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given two arrays nums and andValues of length n and m respectively. The value of an array is equal to the last element of that array. You have to divide nums into m disjoint contiguous subarrays such that for the i<sup>th</sup> subarray [l<sub>i</sub>, r<sub>i</sub>], the bitwise AND of the subarray elements is equal to andValues[i], in other words, nums[l<sub>i</sub>] &amp; nums[l<sub>i</sub> + 1] &amp; ... &amp; nums[r<sub>i</sub>] == andValues[i] for all 1 &lt;= i &lt;= m, where &amp; represents the bitwise AND operator. Return the minimum possible sum of the values of the m subarrays nums is divided into. If it is not possible to divide nums into m subarrays satisfying these conditions, return -1.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: nums = [1,4,3,3,2], andValues = [0,3,3,2]<br/>
                Output: 12<br/>
                Explanation: The only possible way to divide nums is: [1,4] as 1 &amp; 4 == 0. [3] as the bitwise AND of a single element subarray is that element itself. [3] as the bitwise AND of a single element subarray is that element itself. [2] as the bitwise AND of a single element subarray is that element itself. The sum of the values for these subarrays is 4 + 3 + 3 + 2 = 12.<br/><br/>
                Input: nums = [2,3,5,7,7,7,5], andValues = [0,7,5]<br/>
                Output: 17<br/>
                Explanation: There are three ways to divide nums: [[2,3,5],[7,7,7],[5]] with the sum of values 5 + 7 + 5 = 17. [[2,3,5,7],[7,7],[5]] with the sum of values 7 + 7 + 5 = 19. [[2,3,5,7,7],[7],[5]] with the sum of values 7 + 7 + 5 = 19. The minimum possible sum of values is 17.<br/><br/>
                Input: nums = [1,2,3,4], andValues = [2]<br/>
                Output: -1<br/>
                Explanation: The bitwise AND of the entire array nums is 0. As there is no possible way to divide nums into a single subarray to have the bitwise AND of elements equal to 2, return -1.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int minimumValueSum(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; nums, vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; andValues) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int m = andValues.size();
        
        // dp[i][j] = minimum sum using first i elements and first j andValues
        map&lt;pair&lt;int, int&gt;, int&gt; dp;
        
        function&lt;int(int, int, int)&gt; solve = [&amp;](int idx, int andIdx, int currentAnd) -&gt; int {
            if (andIdx == m) {
                return (idx == n) ? 0 : INT_MAX / 2;
            }
            
            if (idx == n) {
                return INT_MAX / 2;
            }
            
            auto key = make_pair(idx * 1000 + andIdx, currentAnd);
            if (dp.count(key)) {
                return dp[key];
            }
            
            int newAnd = currentAnd &amp; nums[idx];
            int result = INT_MAX / 2;
            
            // Option 1: Continue current subarray
            if (newAnd &gt;= andValues[andIdx]) {
                result = min(result, solve(idx + 1, andIdx, newAnd));
            }
            
            // Option 2: End current subarray if AND matches
            if (newAnd == andValues[andIdx]) {
                int nextResult = solve(idx + 1, andIdx + 1, (1 &lt;&lt; 20) - 1);
                if (nextResult != INT_MAX / 2) {
                    result = min(result, nums[idx] + nextResult);
                }
            }
            
            return dp[key] = result;
        };
        
        int result = solve(0, 0, (1 &lt;&lt; 20) - 1);
        return (result &gt;= INT_MAX / 2) ? -1 : result;
    }
};</code></pre>
